body:
resolves #31315

This PR unifies the `SyntheticEvent` from `@types/react` and the `NativeSyntheticEvent` from `@types/react-native` by extending a base interface. This allows generic event handlers that can be used by either React DOM or React Native applications.

```tsx
function eventHandler<T extends React.BaseSyntheticEvent>(e: T) { ... }

// DOM
function UI() {
  return (
    <button onClick={eventHandler}>
      Click me
    </button>
  );
}

// Native
function UI( {
  return (
    <TouchableHighlight onPress={eventHandler}>
      <Text>Press me</Text>
    </TouchableHighlight>
  );
}
```

The [`SyntheticEvent`](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/blob/2bd0b3271c992ed9c22055f7151216f64afd7a3b/types/react/index.d.ts#L909-L935) and [`NativeSyntheticEvent`](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/blob/0d4d1453b2e21c6273ec4a7d2496bfc56a77dc45/types/react-native/index.d.ts#L362-L378) interfaces share the same properties and only differ in three property types:

| property | @types/react | @types/react-native |
|---|---|---|
| nativeEvent | Event | T |
| target | EventTarget | NodeHandle |
| currentTarget | EventTarget & T | NodeHandle |

This PR creates a `BaseSyntheticEvent` type with generics for these three properties.

**Notes:**

1. I set the default values for the generic types to `any` right now and would appreciate input on better default choices.

2. The `BaseSyntheticEvent` name is something of a placeholder. Ideally it would be `SyntheticEvent` and the DOM events would be `DOMSyntheticEvent` (to pair with the `NativeSyntheticEvent`), but that would be a breaking change.

3. I added tests to verify that a function that expects a `BaseSyntheticEvent` works when passed a `MouseEvent` (for DOM) and a `GestureResponderEvent` (for native). Are there any other tests that should be added?

